Our final new speaker is Rasheeda Gray! Named a House Beautiful Next Wave Designer and Philadelphia Tribune’s Most Influential, Founder and Principal Designer Rasheeda Gray’s design journey began after a decade long c-suite career in Marketing. Rasheeda holds a Bachelor of Science in Marketing and International Business, a design certification from Temple University and a Master of Business Administration, (MBA). Rasheeda’s community-based work includes mentoring design students from Drexel University, New York School of Interior Design, Temple University and more. She is a guest speaker at many career days across Philadelphia, has spoken to corporations like PECO/Exelon, Business and Women's empowerment conferences, and has donated design services to local school teacher’s lounges in partnership with PTOs in the Philadelphia area. Rasheeda is a member of Delta Sigma Theta Sorority Inc. and also serves the co-founder of Gray Real Estate Group, a real estate development company, along-side her husband, Jake. Together they have two children, Jacob Jr. and Kennedy.

Rasheeda's work has been celebrated across many media outlets including A&E’s Sell This House, HGTV’s Flea Market Flip and various publications including Robb Report, Architectural Digest, Boston Globe, Better Homes & Gardens, Elle Decor, Philadelphia Magazine, The Philadelphia Inquirer as well as a resident design expert on Good Day Philadelphia.

For more information on Rasheeda's programs on entrepreneurship and the value of relationships in getting dream jobs for your students, visit www.greekuniversity.org/rasheeda

It’s my birthday! 🎉 And what better way to start the day then saying hi to my IG community and for anyone new here, introduce myself!

My name is Rasheeda Gray and I am an Interior Designer, Real Estate Developer, Speaker and former/current (depends on the day 😄) Marketing Professional! If you love interior design, design inspiration and tips with a little motivation along the way… you’re in the right place! 

I launched Gray Space 7 years ago. And after a 15 year corporate marketing career in insurance… decided to turn my passion into my purpose and follow my dreams of becoming an Interior Designer. 

I worked both careers for 3 years… 😅 and went full time 4 years ago. I didn’t know it at the time but my corporate career has prepared me for Entrepreneurship in ways that I could have never imagined. Grateful for the journey!

Today, Gray Space is a team of four; Megan, Felicia, Lexi and we’ve been lucky to work on over 120+ projects across the Philadelphia area and nationwide (we just completed a project in Montana)! 

Our work has been featured in House Beautiful, Architectural Digest, The Robb Report, Boston Globe, Elle Decor, HGTV, Good Day Philadelphia with @jennfredfox29 and in 2021 we were named a House Beautiful Next Wave, in 2022 Most Influential by @phillytrib and I have a new announcement/honor to share tomorrow!!! 😊 

Personally, I grew up in the both Phiiladelphia and Fayetteville, NC and so I say that I have city girl hustle with a southern girl heart ❤️ 

My husbae and business partner Jake is a General Contractor and owner of @graycandc . Our lives and purposes are centered Creating Community, one home at a time and so in addition to construction, he is an insurance agent of 12 years and educates his clients on generational wealth and the power of proper insurance.  Together we are parents to the most amazing children… Jacob & Kennedy!

Thanks for being here in this IG community and sharing my birthday with me! Drop a line to say how you found us or just to wish me a HAPPY BIRTHDAY!!! 🎉 
📸 @vstro

Fireplaces are our thing! 

Whether real or faux here are a few reasons why fireplaces are our favorite:

1️⃣ Warmth and Comfort: The crackling flames create a comforting ambiance. It's the perfect spot to unwind with a hot cup of cocoa or your favorite book.

2️⃣ Aesthetically Pleasing: Fireplaces instantly elevate the look of any room, becomes the focal point of the space and adds a touch of elegance.

3️⃣ Cozy Gatherings: Fireplaces naturally draw people together. Whether it's a family gathering or an intimate date night.

4️⃣ Stress Relief: Watching the dancing flames can be soothing and relaxing.

Here are a few our of projects with fireplaces over the years. Do you like fireplaces? Do you prefer wood burning, gas or electric?

A home office can both look… and feel good!

The goal is PROGRESS not PERFECTION! The question I’m asked most often is how I got started… and my answer has always been, “I just simply got started”. 

I started with what I had… and made improvements along the way! My design process, pricing structure and even design acumen has improved year over year! 

Like many designers my personal home is my canvas. Swipe to see my before which was featured in @phillyinquirer in 2018! The goal is to release a service or product that is "good enough" and keep refining it until it becomes perfect. #oneroomchallenge

Anxiety… Over the last few years I’ve been struggling with anxiety. It started in 2019, shortly after I lost my grandmother and one of my best friends, within a few months of each other.  At first, I thought I was going through early menopause... I would suddenly feel my heart race and body temperature rising. It would feel paralyzing and I would have to stop and breathe. Then when I quit my corporate career to pursue full-time entrepreneurship it became increasingly worse. Then the pandemic hit and what I thought were hot flashes… wouldn’t stop. Life’s curve balls kept coming my way and soon it felt like I couldn’t control it…. So I sought help. I now have an amazing therapist who has taught me ways that I can manage this sometimes crippling diagnosis.  Deep breathing exercises, asking for help, talking with friends and family, challenging negative thoughts and physical exercise are a few coping strategies that have worked well for me. 

Today I felt overwhelmed… and I felt the symptoms coming on… so I closed my laptop, got on the floor and did a five minute breathing exercise. It worked. It feels super vulnerable to share this, but I feel like we don’t talk about it enough. My hope and prayer is that this is helpful to anyone else out there…  going through the same thing. 

XoXo, Rasheeda

This is a fun audio but no… What does an interior designer really do? We create functional and aesthetically pleasing interior spaces. Here are some of our key responsibilities:

1. **Space Planning:** Assess and plan the layout of interior spaces, ensuring efficient use of space and flow within a room or building.

2. **Color and Material Selection:** Select appropriate color schemes, materials, textures, and finishes to enhance the visual appeal and functionality of a space.

3. **Furniture and Fixture Selection:** Source furniture, lighting, window treatments, fixtures, and accessories that align with the design concept and your preferences.

4. **Budget Management:** Work within budget parameters, helping you make smart, cost-effective choices while maintaining design quality.

5. **Client Consulting:** Collaborate closely with our clients to understand your needs, preferences, and lifestyle, tailoring designs to meet those specific requirements.

6. **Design Concept Development:** Interior designers create design concepts and design boards that outline the overall look and feel of a space.

7. **Project Coordination:** Oversee various aspects of the project, including working with contractors, architects, and suppliers to ensure the design is executed correctly and on time.

8. ** Compliance:** We are knowledgeable about building codes and regulations to ensure that designs meet legal requirements.

9. **Staying Updated:** We stay up-to-date with industry trends, emerging technologies, and innovative materials to provide clients with the latest design options.

10. In essence, we combine creativity with practical knowledge to create functional and aesthetically pleasing interior spaces that meet the unique needs and preferences of our clients. 

We turn dreams into reality!

Author and VIP June Reese lends her thoughtful eye and powerful writing, weaving together inspiring interiors and the fascinating personal stories of each featured designer.

Featuring 50 industry stars, Reese tells their stories and shares their challenges and triumphs. Design philosophies and creative influences are brought to light and are illuminated with wonderfully designed spaces in a range of styles. The result is a behind-the-scenes look at what it means to be a person of color creating work in the design industry today.

A portion of the proceeds from each book will go towards funding educational programs, initiatives and resources curated by @blackinteriordesignersinc  with a focus on creating a more intentional industry committed to equality and equity.

One of the hardest and best decisions I ever made was to walk away from my 15 year career in Marketing as an AVP… to follow my dreams of becoming an Interior Designer. I may have been a little delusional 🤣😩 but the confidence that it took to go from my first project in 2016 (my nephew’s nursery) to one of my most successful projects (designing for an NFL player)… was a result of consistency, hard work and faith. 

I wish I could say it’s been roses ever since… but the truth is… my confidence comes and goes. One minute I’m so proud of work that our team has done and in the next minute... I’m thinking about going back to Marketing. 😩 I’ve learned over these last 7 years that entrepreneurship isn’t a neat, straight line. It’s a journey filled with lots of highs and lows… it’s humbling, it’s scary, it’s exciting, it’s rewarding… it can burn you out and energize you all in the same day! 

But when your work is connected to something greater than yourself… whether it’s entrepreneurship… or teaching… a lawyer, doctor… really anything… when you feel like giving up, that’s when God shows up to get you through! My prayer is that you are a little delusional at times… That you walk in faith and that don’t give up even when you don’t have the confidence!

Here’s How👇🏼
.
.
.
1️⃣Measure the room: Measure the dimensions of the room, including the length and width. This will give you an idea of the maximum size your rug can be.

2️⃣ Decide on the placement: Determine where you want to place the rug. Will it be as under furniture or in the center of the room.

3️⃣ Leave space around the edges: It’s generally recommended to leave some space between the rug and the walls or furniture. A common rule of thumb is to leave about 18 inches of bare floor around the edges of the room.

4️⃣ Consider the room’s shape: For square or rectangular rooms, choose a rug that matches the shape of the room. In more irregularly shaped rooms, you can use a square or round rug to create a focal point.

5️⃣ Furniture on or off the rug: In the living room, you can either have all the furniture legs on the rug or just the front legs. In dining rooms, ensure the rug accommodates both the table and chairs when they are pulled out.

6️⃣ Layer rugs: You can also layer different size rugs for a unique look, but make sure they complement each other in terms of size, style, and color.

7️⃣ Consider traffic flow: Ensure the rug’s size allows for easy movement and traffic flow within the room.

Ultimately, the right size rug is one that fits your room’s dimensions, accommodates your furniture, and enhances the overall look and feel of the space.

3 Interior Design Tips I Wish I Knew Earlier…

1.  Don’t follow the rules: Rules are meant to be broken, but there are a few that are non-negotiable. Some of my top non-negotiables are; Curtains must touch or slightly sweep the floor, rugs must be larger than the furniture it’s under and always measure to ensure proper scale for furniture and decor elements. 

2. Your style is in! Honor what you love and if you’re not sure, Pinterest is your best friend. If you don’t know where to start, do a search on Pinterest, and then once you find it image you like, look at the words that the image description or look at the suggested images on Pinterest. Save those images and analyze all of them together to determine, what’s the common thread. That’s how you discover your personal style. 

3. Don’t buy everything at once: Start with the larger pieces like your sofa, chairs, dining table, lighting, etc. and then add personality overtime by collecting decor, pillows, curtains, rugs, etc. 

Follow for more tips! 💡
